7367482619048643886.voice_to_text: now you are right from the certain point of view but I feel like you're only looking at a small part of a bigger picture here yes video games board games heck you can throw in books movies TV shows and comics in there too they're all forms of entertainment that can distract us and give us an escape from the reality around us but just saying that their forms of distraction is actually ignoring the amount of influence that these forms of entertainment can have on us games movies books all these forms of entertainment can inspire us with relatable characters and experiences that can encourage us to be better versions of ourselves they can educate us about the real world issues that are around us and how to act when confronted with them it takes two papers please diaries of a Spaceport janitor these are three examples of video games just off the top of my head that presents players with real life issues forces them to confront them and thus educating them about these issues in fact the gaming industry has a unique practicality to addressing these issues and I'm not saying this as someone who's designing a silly board game about Pirate Dogs I'm saying this as someone who's day job includes gamification and using game like elements to educate people about real world issues when you combine game like elements with real world issues and scenarios you can better gain people's interest engage them in a meaningful way and help them retain the information about these issues and I know this may not be the type of conversation you were expecting to have but if we do encourage people to use these forms of entertainment as more than just a distraction then we can do a lot of good in this world

7375186127352810784.voice_to_text: The Call of duty cheat maker forced to pay over $15 million to Activision, has refused to do it and vowed to keep creating exploits for Modern Warfare 3 and Warzone. Earlier this week, the California courts ruled in favor of Activision in their lawsuit against engine owning, who sell cheats for games like call of Duty, Counter Strike, and battlefield in order to pay that massive sum to Activision and hand over ownership of their website domain to them. Activision first sued engine owning under DMCA, the American copyright law that Bungie also used in their own Destiny 2 cheating lawsuit recently. You won that one in Activision followed suits, or at least in theory, because engine owning is quite simply refusing to comply. They claiming that the people targeted by the lawsuit are long inactive and have even backed up their domain to try and circumvent the forced hand over to Activision. This might seem like a silly response, but it does put Activision in a biz of a bind. They'd have to spend even more of their money, or really your money that you gave them for a slightly shinier pistol, on further legal battles. Some of those could even be outside the United States, which put their odds at the same place as your odds of getting a refund from them. What do you think engine owning brave gamers for standing up against big evil Activision? Or should they finally put down the cheats and just get good Let us know.

Player behavior is a complex problem space. Our systems cannot catch everything. They require constant attention and tweaking and improvement. Sometimes it has to be painfully manual or dependent on our players reporting things and on our processes staying well tuned. But at the end of the day, there are still some people in this world who want to take out their insecurity or their bad day or their whatever on some stranger through their computer screen. And that's exactly what we're experiencing and addressing right now. But I also wanna make sure that I say this out loud. We have no room for these types of behaviour in our game or in our community. Valorant is a team game. It's better played as a team. The strats are better, all of it's better. When you tell someone to just mute comms to avoid harassment, you are essentially putting the harassed person in a position to not communicate, to compromise how they wanna play the game to accommodate you. Muting is a tool for people who choose to use it, not something that is there to justify bad behaviours. Competitive games need to have room for banter. We believe this and I do understand the fear. The fear that we will sanitize gaming by over addressing these issues. We have no interest in doing that. We do believe that a person should not be in a position to have to grow a thicker skin or whatever other unhelpful suggestions have been thrown out there just to avoid threats of violence or literal hate speech. There's no room in our community for the most egregious behaviors, and we're not going to compromise on that point. If you need to make truly evil statements under the guise of regular shit talk to enjoy gaming, then please play something else. We won't miss you. Look, I know this message is intense, so let me say this. This is not just about preventing the worst. It's about promoting the best in each of us. It's about ensuring that people can share in the joy of the matches. One and the tough losses. And the amazing feeling of community that gaming can create.

7374104085739375914.voice_to_text: So the people who defend skill based matchmaking are always saying stuff like, you just wanna win when you play online. All right, bring it. Yes, that is 100% the reason that I play competitive games, because I wanna win. I see it's already been brought in. For those unfamiliar with the term, skill based matchmaking refers, as the name suggests, to matching people up with similar skill levels in video games in particular. And I suspect even those who are not familiar with that specific term immediately recognize how this is an almost universal thing we do in competition. More generally, outside of an occasional exhibition activity. We don't see grandmasters in chess routinely beating up on new chess players or World Cup finalist beating up on elementary school soccer players. And we don't see these things because putting two people who are significantly different in skill level into a competitive activity prevents the person who is of lower skill level from actually learning anything. And it makes the win by the higher skilled player fairly meaningless. The new player not only learns nothing because the game typically is over so quickly there's not a chance to practice and learn, but the skilled player has not really demonstrated any sort of skill. And so for those who are against skill based matchmaking, I have the following question. What is it about winning that's so important that you'd be willing to sacrifice any of the intrigue or interest in the Game in order to avoid the opposite losing where is the enjoyment or even demonstration of skill when, for example, a world champion arm wrestler successfully defeats a toddler? At what point does winning lose all meaning in life? Cause for me, winning a competition that was never a competition at all isn't really a win either.

7369062678939176235.voice_to_text: X defiant is about to be a top three FPS game, all thanks to a major decision that players have been begging to see from call of duty. The peak call of duty games and X defiant actually have a lot of things in common, one of them being the brains behind the operation, Mark Rubin, who worked for Activision as the executive producer during the Modern Warfare series. But more importantly, he understands better than anyone that skill based matchmaking has played a huge factor in a call of duty struggles. So today the team released a statement confirming there will be no skill based matchmaking in the casual playlist for X Defiance. The statement continues on saying skill based matchmaking means every casual game is repetitive, constantly repeating matches that are just as stressful as ranked. We believe casual playlist should be fun and varied, similar to how prime call of duty was. X defiant will find matches in order of these priorities latency avoided, players, party size, region, input device, and then platform. Once in the lobby. Teams will still be balanced though. They also confirmed that ranked will be added in a future season, and those matches will be prioritized based on ranked points.

7364540030037101867.video_description: How to Make "Nuka Cola Quantum" from Fallout #fallout #nukacola #cooking #recipe
7364540030037101867.voice_to_text: Ever wonder what Nuka Cola Quantum tastes like in real life? Well, here's the official recipe. Mix together one cup of water, two cups of sugar, the zest of both a lemon and a lime for a burst of flavor in every glowing sip, two tablespoons of pomegranate juice and two tablespoons of fruit punch. Heat the mixture over medium flame, whisking until the sugar dissolves completely. Bring it to a boil, then lower the heat and let it simmer gently for 10 minutes. Strain into a sealed container. Squeeze in fresh lemon juice and lime juice along with 1 teaspoon of citric acid for a tangy twist. Lastly, add 5 drops of neon blue food dye for that radioactive glow. Allow it to cool, cover tightly and refrigerate. Assemble with ice 9 tablespoons of the syrup and top with Seltzer water. Stir it up and voila! Your very own taste of the waistland awaits. Bottoms up!

7361238969427873070.voice_to_text: Fortnite has gone too far and is now censoring emotes because they might make players feel bad. During the most recent update, Fortnite brought back the Tactical AR, a new Nike collab, Billie Eilish appearance, and more. But this update also comes with some controversy. Under the social privacy menu, you'll now find a new see confrontational emotes setting. And when enabled, instead of user actually seeing the emote, instead they'll see the player who is emoting just standing still with no emote sound. Many players have been complaining about how sweaty and toxic Fortnite has become, so epic says that they're doing this because they want emotes to be a source of good vibes. This new setting applies to the laugh it up emote, whip crack, make it plantain, and the iconic take the out. It's also safe to say that we likely won't be getting any new confrontational emotes in Fortnite anytime soon.

7361185255295962414.video_description: Ben Hall Investigates: Unused mental health beds #benhallinvestigates  #jails  #mentalhealth  #treatment
7361185255295962414.voice_to_text: We're in the middle of a mental health crisis, but Nashville has this place where if you're arrested you can get mental health help. It's something they're trying to create all around the country, but we found ours is almost always empty. Davidson County Sheriff Daron Hall spearheaded the Behavioral Care Center -  tired of seeing mentally ill people locked up - he used money from his jail budget to build a treatment facility inside the jail. Daily jail logs reveal  the BCC has 60 beds, but many times over the last year only about 15 of those were filled. Some days the program had as few as 10 participants, meaning 50 beds in the highly touted program were sitting empty. And that's very concerning it runs at about 20% occupancy at best. Judge Melissa Blackburn oversees Davidson County's Mental Health Court. After seeing the numbers, she thinks there's room to help more people. NewsChannel 5 Investigates questioned Judge Blackburn about this man, Johnson Lloyd, who sat in the Davidson County Jail for nearly a year waiting on a mental health evaluation. When he was finally found incompetent, he was released. He then went up to Bowling Green, where he was arrested for raping a woman. I know they do not take dangerous individuals or very difficult individuals, but he may have been someone once medicated, he may not have been. Why are there so many empty beds? So it was never targeting to solve the mental health problem, and all the people who complain about bed counts, I wish they would call me. Some do, here's what I would tell you, you weren't around helping me design what we needed. So are you disappointed that it's only about 20 to 30% full? No it only is designed to treat a certain type mental illness. The sheriff says the center cannot treat severely mentally ill people. There are no locks on the doors. It's designed for people who need basic help like getting back on their meds  to keep them out of the criminal justice system. But projections from years ago when it was being built, calculated half of everyone arrested would qualify for the BCC and it's beds would be full. The sheriff says arrests are down dramatically. When he planned the BCC, he says 100 people a day were being arrested. That number went down during covid and it's not gone back up. He says now 60 people a day are arrested. The sheriff says it's up to the state to build more hospitals to treat the severely mentally ill. But I wanna know what you think.
